1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 {The Advance/Nimzovich System is the third most
important way to meet the French. By defining the central structure at once,
White strongly restricts Black's possibilities, which may be psychologically
effective against players who prefer to answer 3.Nd2 and 3.Nc3 with 3...dxe4
or other lines with an open centre. But objectively, this system also allows
Black to start his central counterplay at once, in the best spirit of the
French defence.} c5 {It is hard to imagine a position where this thematical
way of undermining the centre is more natural than here. In this section we
will examine a series of minor alternatives for White on move 4.} 4. Qg4 {
The early queen incursion is more typical after Black has developed his king's
bishop (most frequently in the 3.Nc3 Bb4 lines). In the current position is
fails to gain a tempo by attacking g7, but tries to prepare a slow kingside
attack based on massing the pieces on this wing. The drawback of the last move:
It neglects the fight for the central squares, implying at least a temporary
pawn sacrifice.} ({With development still being in its initial phase, White
has no chances for a blockade on the dark squares after} 4. dxc5 Bxc5 5. Qg4 {
The only logical way to justify the last move. After the bishop's departure
from the kingside, Black needs to take a decision regarding the g7-square.} ({
After} 5. Bd3 Nc6 6. Nf3 f6 {, White is likely to lose stability in the centre.
} 7. Qe2 fxe5 8. Nxe5 Nxe5 9. Qxe5 Nf6 10. Bb5+ Kf7 11. O-O Rf8 12. Nd2 Kg8 13.
Qe2 e5 $17 {Westermeier,A (2305)-Darga,K (2495) Germany 1981 (0-1, 23) The
bishop's pressure along the g1-a7 diagonal is killing.}) 5... Ne7 $1 {As in
many Winawer lines (which are not part of our repertoire, though) rapid
development is no less important than the attacked pawn.} 6. Qxg7 (6. b4 {
runs into the intermediate move} h5 7. Qxg7 Rg8 8. Qh7 Bxb4+ 9. c3 Qc7 $17 {
Banas,J (2395)-Vilela de Acuna,J (2460) Trnava 1979 (0-1, 16)}) 6... Rg8 7.
Qxh7 Qb6 8. Nh3 Nbc6 9. f4 Bd7 10. c3 O-O-O {Black's advance in development is
bigger than in the Winawer system, which suggests that White is in some
trouble already.} 11. b4 (11. Qd3 Nf5 12. Na3 Be7 13. Nf2 Kb8 14. g3 d4 {
Black is fully developed and his initiative more than compensates for the
pawns.}) 11... Nxb4 $1 12. cxb4 Bxb4+ 13. Bd2 Qe3+ 14. Be2 {Carranza Caba,
P-Chalmeta Ugas,J Spain 2000 (0-1, 17)} Bb5 15. Qc2+ Nc6 16. Nc3 Bxc3 17. Bxc3
Rxg2 $19) (4. f4 {is likely to transpose to 5.f4 in Line 3, as White cannot
delay c2-c3 forever:} Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Bd3 Bd7 7. O-O Nh6) ({The bishop is
not the best suited blocking piece on d4 after} 4. Be3 cxd4 5. Bxd4 Nc6 6. c3 (
6. Bb5 Bd7 {threatens ...Nxe5, more or less forcing} 7. Bxc6 bxc6 {, offering
Black the two bishops and a mobile centre.}) 6... Nge7 7. Nf3 Nf5 8. Be2 {
Ljubicic,F (2396)-Zaja,I (2443) Pula 1999 (0-1, 31)} g5 $5 {One of the
consequences of the early bishop departure from its initial diagonal.} 9. h3 h5
10. Nbd2 Rh6 11. Nb3 g4 $15) ({The main line} 4. c3 {will be examined in
detail below.}) 4... Nc6 5. Nf3 ({It is already too late to consolidate the
d4-pawn:} 5. c3 cxd4 6. cxd4 Qb6 7. Nf3 Nh6 {, followed by ...Nf5, and White
cannot avoid loss of material.} 8. Bxh6 Qxb2 $1 $17) 5... cxd4 6. Bd3 {We will
see a similar developing pattern in Line 2. White has ensured the bishop's
stability on d3, but Black's extra pawn is likely to tell after the expected ..
.f7-f6.} Qc7 7. Qg3 ({If} 7. Bf4 Nb4 $5 $146 {the queen's absence from the
centre suddenly becomes a problem:} 8. Nxd4 (8. O-O Nxd3 9. cxd3 h5 10. Qg3 Qc2
11. Nbd2 Qxd3 $17 {The queen has won a pawn and is ready to return to the
defence.}) 8... Nxd3+ 9. cxd3 Qb6 10. Nb3 Qb4+ 11. Ke2 (11. N1d2 $2 g5 12. Qxg5
Bh6 $19) 11... Ne7 $15 (11... g5 12. Qxg5 Bh6 13. Bd2 $1)) 7... f6 {In the
absence of a white pawn on d4 this break usually offers Black a pawn advantage
in the centre.} 8. exf6 (8. Bxh7 Nxe5 9. Bg6+ Kd8 $17) (8. Bf4 g5 $1 9. Bd2 (9.
Nxg5 fxg5 10. Qxg5 Bg7 $19) 9... Nxe5 $17 10. Nxe5 $2 Qxe5+ {0-1 Araiza Munoz,
J-Fine,R Syracuse, NY 1934}) 8... Qxg3 9. f7+ Kxf7 10. hxg3 Bd6 $5 $146 {
It appears that the opening of the h-file does not enable white to retrieve
the pawn under favourable circumstances.} 11. Ng5+ (11. Bxh7 Nge7 {[%cal Gg7g6]
followed by .. .g7-g6 traps the bishop soon.}) 11... Ke7 12. f4 Nf6 13. Nd2 e5
14. fxe5 Nxe5 15. O-O h6 16. Ngf3 Nxd3 17. cxd3 Bf5 $17 {With two active
bishops and space advantage for Black.} *

