1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Nf3 {The line examined here was advocated by
Nimzovich. As in the previous line, White ignores the centre and tries to
speed up his kingside attack. This system is sounder than the previous one as
the queen on d1 allows him to keep some balance between the wings.} Nc6 {
As usual, I prefer developing moves when given a choice.} (4... cxd4 {may just
transpose below.}) 5. Bd3 (5. Bb5 Bd7 {faces White with the familiar threat ...
Nxe5, more or less forcing him to make a decision.} 6. Bxc6 (6. Bd3 cxd4 {
gains a tempo over the main line below.}) 6... bxc6 7. c3 (7. O-O cxd4 {
allows Black to put his pawns into motion.}) 7... cxd4 8. cxd4 c5 9. O-O cxd4
10. Nxd4 Ne7 11. f4 Ng6 12. Nc3 Bc5 {Black has harmonious development and no
problems at all, as f4-f5 is not likely to become an issue soon. Black could
later choose between kingside play based on ...f7-f6 and queenside pressure
with ... a7-a5-a4, or even combine these plans.}) (5. dxc5 {once again
prematurely releases the tension.} Bxc5 6. Bb5 ({White needs to fight for the
central dark squares as after} 6. Bd3 f6 7. exf6 Nxf6 8. O-O O-O {Black gets
too much activity.} 9. c4 dxc4 10. Bxc4 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Ng4 12. Rf1 Nd4 13. Nbd2
b5 14. Bd3 Bb7 $17 {Becker,A-Eliskases,E Vienna 1935 (1/2-1/2, 68)}) 6... Nge7
$146 7. O-O O-O 8. Nbd2 Ng6 9. Nb3 Bb6 10. Qe2 Qc7 11. Re1 f6 12. exf6 Rxf6
$132) (5. c3 {transposes to the main lines, starting with Line 3.}) 5... cxd4
6. O-O ({White cannot afford slow plans such as} 6. a3 {preparing b4 and Bb2
as Black can react in the centre at once with} f6 $17 7. Bb5 $2 Qa5+) 6... Nge7
{Preparing ...Ng6, which usually forces Bxg6, strengthening Black's structure.}
7. Bf4 ({The other way to consolidate the e-pawn is} 7. Re1 Ng6 8. Nbd2 Qc7 9.
Bxg6 hxg6 10. Nb3 f6 {Due to Black's compact mass of pawns and White's
incomplete development, the king's presence in the centre does not face Black
with dangers after this typical move.} 11. Nbxd4 (11. Bf4 g5 12. Bg3 Qb6 13.
exf6 gxf6 14. Nbxd4 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 Bd7 16. Qd3 Kf7 17. Rad1 Bc5 $11) 11... Nxe5
12. Bf4 Nxf3+ 13. Qxf3 Qb6 14. Qxd5 Kf7 15. Qc4 Bc5 16. Rad1 {Beikert,G (2475)
-Schlindwein,R (2425) Germany 1997 (1/2-1/2, 36)} Qb4 {Forcing the queen
exchange.} 17. Qxb4 Bxb4 18. c3 Be7 19. Nb5 e5 20. Be3 b6 21. Nd6+ Bxd6 22.
Rxd6 g5 $11) (7. Nbd2 Qc7 8. Re1 Ng6 {transposes.}) 7... Ng6 8. Bg3 Be7 9. Nbd2
f5 10. exf6 gxf6 {Black has kept his extra pawn so far and has an impressive
central structure. White needs to look for ways to grab the initiative based
on the king's relative exposure.} 11. Nh4 f5 $5 {Neutralizing the d3-bishop's
pressure.} 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. Bb5 (13. Nf3 g5 $5 $146 14. Be5 Kf7 $5 15. Bxh8
Qxh8 16. c4 dxc3 17. bxc3 g4 18. Nd4 Nxd4 19. cxd4 Bd6 20. g3 Qxd4 {With two
pawns for the exchange, an active dark-squared bishop and a compact structure,
Black is certainly not worse.}) {Hagarova,Z (2364)-Berescu,A (2491) Banska
Stiavnica 2006 (1/2-1/2, 24)} 13... g5 14. Be5 Rh7 15. Nf3 (15. f4 g4 16. Nb3
Kf7 {forces White to exchange one of his bishops for the knight, causing him
stability problems.}) 15... Kf7 16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. Bxd4 c5 18. Ne5+ Kg8 19. Nc6
{It is a good idea to strive for simplifications before the pawns and the
possible attack along the h-file become threatening.} Qd6 20. Nxe7+ Kf7 21. f4
cxd4 22. Nxc8 Rxc8 23. Qxd4 Rxc2 24. Qxa7+ Kg6 25. Qe3 Rxb2 26. Rae1 Qb6 $11 *

