1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 {Obviously the most principled move. White
does his best to maintain his early space advantage.} Nc6 {Due to the early
commitment implied by 3.e5, Black has a very simple and effective plan for
counterplay, based on ...Qb6 and ...Ne7(h6)-f5.} 5. Nf3 {The most natural way
to keep control over the centre and doubtlessly the only consistent move.} (5.
f4 {wastes an essential tempo without offering White chances of a kingside
pawn attack.} Qb6 6. Nf3 Nh6 7. Bd3 (7. Na3 cxd4 8. cxd4 Bxa3 9. bxa3 Nf5 {
dooms the d4-pawn.}) 7... cxd4 8. cxd4 Bd7 9. Bc2 Nb4 10. Nc3 Nxc2+ 11. Qxc2
Nf5 12. Qf2 h5 $15) (5. Bb5 Bd7 6. Bxc6 (6. a4 cxd4 $146 7. cxd4 Nge7 8. Ne2
Nf5 9. O-O Be7 {or}) (6. Ba4 Qa5 7. Bxc6 bxc6 {with comfortable black play in
both cases.}) 6... bxc6 7. Nf3 cxd4 8. cxd4 c5 9. O-O cxd4 10. Nxd4 Ne7 11. Nc3
{Pinzon,J (2173)-Acosta,A (2335) Bogota 2011 (1-0, 30)} Ng6 12. f4 Bc5 {
transposing to a position seen in Line 2.}) (5. Be3 {exposes the bishop after}
Nge7 6. Nf3 Nf5 7. Bd3 Qb6 8. Qd2 Nxe3 9. fxe3 Be7 10. O-O Bd7 11. Kh1 f5 12.
exf6 gxf6 (12... Bxf6 $11) 13. c4 dxc4 14. Bxc4 O-O-O 15. Nc3 Na5 16. Bd3 Kb8
$13 {Dvirnyy,D (2480)-Bentivegna,F (2348) Acqui Terme 2011 (1-0, 73)}) 5... Qb6
{In this line we will examine some minor alternatives for White, none of them
facing Black with serious problems.} 6. Qb3 ({White does not have time to
prepare the consolidation of d4 with Bb2, as} 6. b3 $6 cxd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+ 8. Bd2
Nxd4 {loses a pawn.}) ({With the queen on b6 and without the possibility to
castle soon, now is one of the worst moments to give up the centre:} 6. dxc5
Bxc5 7. Qc2 f6 8. Bf4 (8. b4 Be7 9. exf6 Bxf6 $15) (8. exf6 Nxf6 9. b4 Bd6 10.
Bg5 O-O $15) 8... g5 (8... fxe5 9. Nxe5 Nf6 $15) 9. Bg3 g4 10. Nh4 fxe5 $17 {
Perez Beltran,J (1610)-Santos Ruiz,M (2021) Islantilla 2012 (0-1, 36)}) 6...
Qxb3 7. axb3 cxd4 8. cxd4 (8. Nxd4 Nxd4 9. cxd4 Ne7 10. Nc3 Nc6 11. Be3 Bd7 $11
) 8... Bd7 {The control over b4 and the long term weakness of the doubled
pawns offer Black great play.} 9. Bd2 (9. Nc3 Bb4 10. Bd2 Nge7 11. Nb5 O-O $15)
9... f6 10. exf6 (10. Nc3 fxe5 11. dxe5 Nh6 $132) 10... gxf6 $5 (10... Nxf6 11.
Bc3 (11. Bb5 Bd6 12. O-O O-O 13. Nc3 $11 {is a better try.}) 11... Bd6 12. Na3
O-O 13. Bd3 a6 14. Nc2 Nh5 $15 {Boeckler,E (1410)-Buescher,S (1554) Bad
Homburg 2004 (0-1, 25)}) 11. Nc3 Nb4 12. Kd1 Kf7 $15 {Black's more compact
structure offers him the better chances in the long run.} *

