1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Bd3 {This is the most
natural way of continuing the development as White places the bishop on an
attacking diagonal. But even though the triple capture on d4 loses the queen
to о Pb5, the main problem is that the d4-pawn will soon be in danger.} cxd4
$1 ({This is the most accurate move order, as} 6... Bd7 {allows} 7. dxc5 Bxc5
8. O-O {followed by Nbd2-b3 and later Be3, gaining time to establish piece
control on d4.}) 7. cxd4 Bd7 {The threat on d4 is real now.} 8. O-O {The most
principled move, sacrificing the pawn for initiative. But practice has shown
that White's compensation is far from obvious.} (8. Bc2 {allows} Nb4 9. O-O (9.
Bb3 Qa6 $17 {causes problems with the king.}) 9... Nxc2 10. Qxc2 Ne7 11. Nc3
Nf5 12. Qd3 Rc8 13. Bd2 Be7 14. Rac1 O-O $11 {Black has very comfortable play.}
15. g3 (15. g4 $6 Nh4 16. Nxh4 Bxh4 17. g5 Rc4 18. Ne2 Bb5 $15) 15... h6 16.
Kg2 Rc7 {followed by Rfc8.}) (8. Be2 {just wastes a tempo.} Nge7 9. Na3 (9. b3
Nf5 10. Bb2 Bb4+ 11. Kf1 Be7 12. g3 O-O 13. Kg2 f6 14. a3 fxe5 15. dxe5 Bc5 16.
g4 Nh4+ 17. Nxh4 Rxf2+ 18. Kh3 Raf8 19. Nd2 Bd4 20. Ra2 Bxb2 21. Rxb2 Qe3+ 22.
Bf3 Nxe5 $19 {Rubinetti,J (2425)-Barria Zuniga,D (2305) Buenos Aires 1998 (1-0,
30)}) 9... Nf5 10. Nc2 Nb4 11. Nxb4 (11. Ne3 Rc8 12. O-O Nxe3 13. fxe3 Nc2 14.
Rb1 Na3) 11... Bxb4+ 12. Kf1 Bb5 $15) (8. Nc3 Nxd4 9. Nxd4 Qxd4 10. Qe2 a6 {
is likely to transpose below after} 11. O-O) 8... Nxd4 9. Nbd2 {The most
consistent move, aiming for rapid development.} (9. Ng5 Nc6 10. Re1 Bc5 11. Qf3
O-O-O 12. Nc3 f6 13. Na4 (13. exf6 Nxf6 14. Nf7 Rhf8 15. Nxd8 Qxd8 $17 {
causes trouble on f2.} 16. Be3 $2 d4 $19) 13... Qa5 $19 {Roehrich,S (2230)
-Ivanov,S (2505) Cologne 1993 (0-1, 34)}) ({Black's queen is rather active
than exposed after} 9. Nxd4 Qxd4 10. Nc3 a6 $5 {Securing the queenside against
Nb5.} 11. Qe2 Ne7 12. Kh1 Nc6 13. f4 Nb4 14. Rd1 (14. Bb1 Qc4 15. Qd1 d4 16.
Ne4 d3 $17) 14... Bc5 15. Bxa6 Qf2 16. Qxf2 Bxf2 {White has retrieved the pawn,
but the structure favours Black.} 17. Be2 O-O 18. Bd2 Nc2 19. Rab1 Ne3 20. Rdc1
Bc6 21. Bf3 Nc4 $19 {Milesi,L (2223)-Apicella,M (2542) Cap d'Agde 2003 (0-1,
21)}) 9... Nxf3+ {The simplest solution.} 10. Nxf3 Ne7 11. Be3 Qd8 {White is
better developed, but this is difficult to exploit as Black has no weaknesses.}
12. Rc1 (12. Ng5 h6 13. Nh7 Rxh7 $1 14. Bxh7 g6 15. h4 {Cornette,M (2521)
-Arsenault,N (2213) Montreal 2008 (1-0, 30)} h5 16. g4 d4 17. Qxd4 (17. Bxd4
Nc6 18. g5 Nxd4 19. Qxd4 Bc6 $17) 17... Nc6 18. Qe4 Qxh4 19. Bxg6 Ne7 20. gxh5
Nxg6 $1 $17) (12. Bc5 Ng6 13. Bxf8 Nxf8 14. Qd2 Ng6 $15) (12. b4 Ng6 13. a3 Be7
$15) 12... Nc6 13. a3 Be7 14. b4 a6 15. Re1 Qb8 16. Bc5 h6 17. Bb1 Bxc5 18.
Rxc5 {Ker,A (2311)-Libiszewski,F (2530) Palmerston North 2018 (0-1, 44)} Qd8
19. Qd3 Rc8 20. Rec1 Ne7 {White's initiative will soon be extinguished and his
best chance will be to set up a fortress based on the blockade on d4.} *

