1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Na3 $5 {The manoeuvre
Na3-c2 is typical for the Advance variation, providing the d4-pawn with the
necessary defence. But the knight's future prospects are not always clear.}
cxd4 7. cxd4 Bd7 {Black plays in the spirit of Line 7 below.} ({Several
players (including myself in a rapid game) fell into the trap} 7... Bb4+ 8. Bd2
Nxd4 $2 9. Nxd4 Bxa3 10. Bb5+ $1 {losing a piece:} Kd8 11. bxa3 Qxd4 12. Bg5+)
({In the past, 6.Na3 was underestimated, mainly because of} 7... Bxa3 8. bxa3 {
, but lately it appeared that the absence of the dark-squared bishop may cause
problems even if Black wins the a3-pawn.}) 8. Nc2 (8. Be2 {allows Black to
transpose to Line 7, but also offers him a good alternative:} Bb4+ 9. Kf1 Rc8
10. Nc2 Be7 11. g3 Nh6 12. Kg2 f6 13. Bxh6 gxh6 14. exf6 Bxf6 15. Qd2 Bg7) (8.
Bb5 $2 {is a frequent blunder.} Bxa3 9. Bxc6 Bb4+) (8. Nb5 {was twice played,
but it loses a pawn to} Nxe5) ({White has no compensation after} 8. Bd3 Nxd4 9.
O-O (9. Nxd4 Qxd4) 9... Nxf3+ 10. Qxf3 Ne7) 8... Nb4 {The typical way of
clearing space for the queenside counterplay. One of the main ideas is to
exchange the light-squared bishops with ...Bb5.} 9. Ne3 {Enjoying more space,
White should avoid exchanges. Other moves make Black's life easier.} (9. Nxb4
Bxb4+ 10. Bd2 Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2 Bb5 12. Bd3 (12. Bxb5+ Qxb5 13. a4 Qb6 14. O-O Ne7
{1/2-1/2 Ward,C (2505)-Tkachiev,V (2615) Hastings 1997}) (12. Qb4 Bxf1 13. Qxb6
axb6 14. Rxf1 Ne7 15. Kd2 Nc6 16. h4 h6 17. h5 Ke7 18. Rfc1 Ra4 19. b3 Ra3 20.
Kc3 Rha8 21. Rc2 b5 $36 {Cicak,S (2530)-Drozdovskij,Y (2561) Warsaw 2006 (0-1,
41)}) 12... Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Qb4+ 14. Nd2 Rc8 15. O-O Ne7 $11 {Kuzmin,G (2485)
-Brynell,S (2480) Berlin 1994 (1/2-1/2, 26)}) (9. Bd2 {is slightly more
consistent as it does not allow the immediate exchange of all bishops.} Nxc2+
10. Qxc2 Rc8 (10... Bb5 {, as in Arribas Robaina,M (2305)-Delgado Crespo,M 
(2275) Havana 1998 (1/2-1/2, 14) also looks natural, but offers White some
light initiative after} 11. Bxb5+ Qxb5 12. a4 Qd7 13. O-O) 11. Qd3 Bb4 12. Bxb4
(12. Be2 Bxd2+ 13. Qxd2 Bb5 $11) 12... Qxb4+ 13. Qd2 Qxd2+ 14. Kxd2 Ne7 15. Bd3
Nc6 16. Ke3 Ke7 17. Rhc1 a6 18. h4 h6 19. h5 Nb4 {and Black will finally
activate/exchange his bishop with ...Bb5 soon.}) 9... Bb5 10. a3 (10. Bxb5+
Qxb5 {implies the queens' exchange, further simplifying Black's task.} 11. Qe2
a6 12. Qxb5+ axb5 13. Ke2 Nxa2 14. Bd2 Ne7 15. Nc2 Nc6 16. Na3 b4 17. Rxa2 bxa3
18. Rb1 Nd8 {Volokitin,A (2687)-Meier,G (2655) Haguenau 2013 (В1/2-В1/2, 39)}
) 10... Nc6 ({In principle} 10... Bxf1 11. Kxf1 Nc6 {is also OK, but it allows
White to continue his natural regrouping with} 12. g3 {Zvjaginsev,V (2635)
-Chernin,A (2605) Ohrid 2009 (1/2-1/2, 25)}) 11. Be2 a6 ({But now that White
has moved with his bishop already,} 11... Bxe2 12. Qxe2 a6 {, possibly
followed by ...Bb5, is simpler.}) 12. Bxb5 Qxb5 13. Bd2 a5 (13... Qxb2 14. Rb1
Qxa3 15. Rxb7 $36) 14. Bc3 Nge7 15. Ng1 a4 $5 {followed by the weak queenside
square invasion starting with ...Na5.} ({In the following game Black chose the
wrong plan:} 15... Ng6 16. Ne2 f6 17. exf6 gxf6 18. O-O Bh6 19. Ng4 Bg7 20. f4
$36 {Efimenko,Z (2649)-Fridman,D (2635) Germany 2014 (1-0, 49)}) *

