1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Be2 {The second most
important continuation after 6.a3. Unlike in the case of the latter, White
does not force matters, but develops naturally, keeping the d4-pawn protected
at the same time.} cxd4 {There is no such thing as an absolutely restrictive
move order, but after White has made his first commitment, I recommend for
Black to follow suit. Before transfering the undeveloped knight to f5, fixing
the pawn structure certainly makes sense. In practice several other moves have
been tried.} ({After} 6... Nh6 7. Bxh6 {Black should refrain from} Qxb2 $2 8.
Be3 Qxa1 9. Qc2 {, when} cxd4 10. Nxd4 $1 {keeps the queen's trap closed.}) (
6... Nge7 {allows White to change the structure with} 7. dxc5 Qxc5 {Even
though this is all right for Black objectively, I prefer to play against a
stable central structure.}) 7. cxd4 Nge7 (7... Nh6 8. Bxh6 Qxb2 {is entirely
playable now, as the exchange in the centre already took place, depriving
White from Nxd4. But generally, if there is a worthy alternative (the main
line move in this case) I prefer to refrain from early pawn grabbing with
black.}) 8. Nc3 {This is an attempt to provide the d4-pawn with indirect
defence in view of Na4. But the knight will stand badly on the board edge,
offering Black additional options for counterplay.} (8. b3 {prepares to defend
the pawn safely, but gives up the right to castle, thus offering Black a few
tempi to organize his counterplay.} Nf5 9. Bb2 Bb4+ 10. Kf1 Be7 11. Nc3 Qd8 ({
It is probably best to regroup properly before breaking in the centre, but the
immediate} 11... f6 $5 {seems OK, too.} 12. g4 Nh6 13. exf6 gxf6 14. Rg1 Nf7
15. Rc1 {Hong,J (2130)-Sun,Q (2243) Suzhou 2001 (1/2-1/2, 44)} Qc7 {[%cal
Gf7g5] Planning ...Ng5.} 16. h4 Bd7 17. Na4 Nd6 18. Nd2 b6 $13) 12. g3 (12. g4
Nh4 {The typical reaction.} 13. Nxh4 Bxh4 14. Kg2 {Mora Manez,J (2080)
-Manninen,M (2385) Elista 1998 (0-1, 42)} f5 $11 15. gxf5 $2 Qg5+) 12... f6 {
Of course, Black could also castle first, transposing below.} 13. Kg2 O-O 14.
exf6 (14. Rc1 Bd7 15. Na4 b6 16. Re1 fxe5 17. dxe5 Qe8 18. Nc3 Qf7 19. Nb5 Rad8
20. Ba3 Bxa3 21. Nxa3 h6 {1/2-1/2 Brenjo,S (2400)-Petkov,V (2300) Nis 1994} 22.
