1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Be2 cxd4 7. cxd4 Nge7 8. Na3
{This is the most consistent way to defend the pawn.} Nf5 9. Nc2 Bd7 {With
this and the next move Black prepares to take full advantage of the thematic ..
.Nb4. Another option is to deviate with ...Na5 followed by ...Bb5.} 10. O-O Rc8
{Black has finished his neutral moves, but it is White who needs to make a
commitment now.} 11. Kh1 $5 {As far as I understand, the most modern move. Its
idea will be explained on the next move.} (11. b3 {weakens the c3-square,
allowing Black to execute his main plan under comfortable circumstances.} Nb4
12. Ne3 (12. Nxb4 Bxb4 13. Bb2 O-O 14. Qd3 a6 15. a4 Qa5 $5 $146 16. Rfc1 Rxc1+
17. Rxc1 b5 {with strong queenside counterplay.}) (12. Nce1 Bb5 13. Bxb5+ (13.
Bb2 {Baeta,M-Lemos,J Brasilia 1985 (0-1, 28)} Bxe2 14. Qxe2 h5 $15 {Without
light squared bishops and with White's bishop away from the c1-h6 diagonal,
the weaknesses created by this move are irrelevant and Black can enjoy its
main merit, the stability of the knight f5.}) 13... Qxb5 14. g4 Ne7 15. Nh4 {
Bologan,V (2681)-Levin,E (2521) Loo 2013 (1-0, 40)} h5 $1 16. g5 (16. gxh5 g6
$17) 16... g6 $11) 12... Nxe3 13. fxe3 (13. Bxe3 Nc2 {shows the virtues of 10..
.Rc8.} 14. Rc1 Nxe3 15. Rxc8+ Bxc8 16. fxe3 Be7 17. Bd3 Bd7 18. Qc2 g6 19. Qe2
O-O 20. h3 f5 21. exf6 Bxf6 $11 {Marrero Lopez,Y (2274)-Esquivel,L (2094)
Panama City 2013 (1/2-1/2, 24)}) 13... Be7 14. Ne1 O-O (14... Bb5 15. Bxb5+
Qxb5 16. a3 Nc6 17. Nd3 Na5 18. b4 {Kalezic,B (2457)-Draganic,V (2286) Tivat
2011 (1-0, 27)} Nc4 $11) 15. a3 Nc6 16. b4 f6 17. exf6 Bxf6 18. Nf3 Ne7 19. Bd2
Bb5 $11 {Steinitz,W-Showalter,J London 1899 (1/2-1/2, 51) A logically played
opening phase, despite the early epoque when the game took place.}) (11. Rb1 {
evacuates the rook from the knight's range (in view of Black's latent idea ...
Nb4-c2) and defends b2 in order to enable the queen's bishop's development.
But it also creates a pin, with the same effect as b2-b3.} Nb4 12. Nxb4 Bxb4
13. g4 (13. Qd3 a6 {Preparing ...Bb5.} 14. Qb3 Ba5) 13... Ne7 $1 14. Be3 ({
The point is that} 14. a3 $2 {does not trap the bishop due to} Bxa3 $15) 14...
Ng6 15. Ne1 Bxe1 (15... O-O 16. f4 f6 $11 {is simpler.}) 16. Qxe1 {Roca,P 
(2365) -Sayson,A Philippines 1997 (1/2-1/2, 52)} Bb5 17. Bxb5+ Qxb5 18. f4 Rc2
19. f5 Ne7 {with adequate black counterplay. White's kingside attack misses
the main target: the king.}) (11. Bd3 {keeps the pawn indirectly defended, but
soon it will become vulnerable.} Nb4 (11... Ncxd4 $2 12. Nfxd4 Nxd4 13. Be3 Bc5
14. b4 $1 $18) 12. Nxb4 Bxb4 {Planning not only ...Bb5 but also ...Nxd4, as
the pin created by Be3 is not effective due to ...Nxf3+.} 13. Bxf5 exf5 14. Bd2
Be7 15. Bg5 Bf8 $1 16. Rc1 Rxc1 17. Bxc1 h6 18. b3 Be7 19. Qd2 O-O 20. Bb2 Rc8
$15 {Black's bishops are strong and his structure is more mobile.}) (11. a3 {
prevents ...Nb4 mechanically but weakens the light squares, thus justifying}
Na5 {followed by ...Bb5.}) 11... Na5 $5 ({White's point is that after} 11...
Nb4 12. Nxb4 Bxb4 13. g4 Nh6 {(otherwise a3 traps the bishop)} 14. Rg1 {
White stabilizes the kingside to his favour, as the knight is passive on h6.})
12. g4 (12. Ne3 Nxe3 13. fxe3 Be7 $11 14. e4 $5 O-O (14... dxe4 15. Ng5 Bxg5
16. Bxg5 {offered White a strong initiative for the pawn, despite the quick
defeat in Santalla,A (2083)-Sadorra,J (2501) Fort Myers 2016 (0-1, 29)}) 15.
exd5 exd5 $11 {possibly followed by ...f7-f6 soon.}) (12. b3 {may lead to play
on both wings with balanced chances:} Bb5 13. Bxb5+ Qxb5 14. Ne3 Nxe3 15. Bxe3
Be7 16. Ng5 O-O 17. Nh3 Qc6 18. Qg4 Qc2 19. Rac1 Qe4 20. Qe2 Ba3 21. Rxc8 Rxc8
22. Qb5 b6 23. Qd7 Qc2 24. Qxa7 Qxa2 25. Qxb6 Nxb3 26. Qa6 Rc2 27. Ng5 h6 28.
Nxe6 fxe6 29. Qxe6+ Kh8 30. Qxd5 ({Too ambtious. White should have given
perpetual check with} 30. Bxh6 $11) 30... Nd2 $15 {Lagno,K (2507)-Michiels,B 
(2442) Antwerp 2008 (0-1, 57) Black's extra piece is stronger than the pawns
due to the rook's activity along the second rank.}) 12... Ne7 13. Nfe1 Bb5 14.
Nd3 {A consistent plan, preventing the bishop's exchange.} h5 $1 15. gxh5 Nf5
16. Be3 Nc4 (16... g6 {is premature:} 17. hxg6 fxg6 18. Rg1 Qc7 {Grischuk,A 
(2606) -Gulko,B (2643) Esbjerg 2000 (1-0, 35)} 19. Nce1 Qf7 20. Nf3 $16) 17. b3
Ncxe3 18. fxe3 g6 $1 {But now that Black has rid himself of the "knight on the
rim" and weakened the white kingside structure, this is well timed.} 19. a4 Ba6
20. b4 Bc4 21. hxg6 (21. Qd2 Qd8 22. Nc5 Bxe2 23. Qxe2 Bxc5 24. bxc5 Rxh5 $17
25. Rxf5 Rxf5 26. Rf1 Rxf1+ 27. Qxf1 Qa5 28. Qf6 Qd2 {0-1 Jonkman,H (2430)
-Giaccio, A (2462) Pinamar 2006}) 21... Ng3+ (21... fxg6 22. Rf2 Qd8 $44 {
is also possible}) 22. Kg1 Nxf1 23. Qxf1 Qc7 24. Na3 Bxd3 25. Nb5 Qe7 26. Bxd3
(26. Nd6+ Kd7 27. Bxd3 Qg5+ 28. Kh1 Bxd6 29. exd6 Rxh2+ $1 $19) 26... Qg5+ 27.
Kh1 fxg6 28. Nxa7 Rc7 $17 {, with an extra exchange and a strong attack.} *

