1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. a3 {This is the classical
main line and the most ambitious one. White intends to neutralize Black's
pressure with b2-b4. The main drawback of this move is the weakening of the
b3-square, which justifies Black's resolute answer, recommended below:} c4 {
The point is that White will not find it easy to open the queenside with b2-b3
(b4), as this would create a new weakness on c4. Besides, the last move
prevents the most active white bishop's development to d3 and also restricts
other white pieces to some extend. Black can try to stabilize the queenside
and castle long. Since White must castle short, the main events are likely to
take place on the kingside. Even though White has a space advantage on that
wing, the king's presence usually makes the situation double-edged.} (6... a5 {
allows} 7. Bd3 {, as after} cxd4 8. cxd4 Bd7 9. Bc2 {Black does not have ...
Nb4 any more.}) 7. Nbd2 Na5 8. b4 $5 {In this section we will examine only the
minor continuations. The last move is possible, but does not promise an
advantage.} (8. Rb1 Bd7 {more or less transposes if White plays b2-b4 soon.}) (
{Early kingside expansion tends to waste time:} 8. h4 Bd7 9. h5 f5 $1 {
Justified by the time spent by White on advancing his pawn.} 10. Rb1 (10. exf6
gxf6 11. g3 {Shabalov,A (2569)-Milicevic,G (2280) Toronto 2009 (0-1, 30)} e5
$17 12. dxe5 Bc5 13. Qe2 O-O-O 14. Bg2 Re8) 10... Nh6 11. Be2 Be7 12. O-O Rc8
13. Re1 Nf7 14. Qc2 Qc7 15. Nh2 g5 $15 {Shabalov,A (2605)-Akobian,V (2526)
Philadelphia 2004 (0-1, 41)}) 8... cxb3 9. Bb2 {White does not hurry to
retrieve the pawn but prepares to open the centre with c3-c4 instead.} (9. Rb1
Bd7 10. Nxb3 Ba4 {would put him under an unpleasant pin, although the piece
tension may also have a double-edged character if Black is careless.} 11. Nfd2
Rc8 12. Nxa5 (12. Qc2 Qc7 13. Bb2 Nc4 $17) 12... Qxa5 (12... Bxd1 13. Rxb6 axb6
14. Bb5+ {Lukyanov,M (2044)-Shapoval,A (2304) Kiev 2005 (1-0, 58)} Ke7 15. Nxb7
$44) 13. Nb3 Qxc3+ 14. Qd2 (14. Bd2 Qc2 $15) 14... Qxd2+ (14... Bxb3 {Barba
Rios,E (1761)-Barra Sanz,A (1569) Barcelona 2009 (0-1, 42)} 15. Qxc3 Rxc3 16.
Bd2 Rc7 17. Rxb3 $44) 15. Bxd2 b6 $17 {Black is simply a pawn up.}) 9... Bd7
10. c4 Ne7 ({This is more consistent than} 10... dxc4 11. Nxc4 Nxc4 12. Bxc4
Ne7 13. O-O Bc6 14. Bxb3 {, offering White an advantage in development, which
is at least as relevant as Black's blockade on d5.}) 11. c5 {White does not
have neutral useful moves left, so he needs to gain space.} Qc7 12. Bd3 Ba4 13.
Rc1 b5 (13... b6 {is more accurate, with a possible transposition to the main
line after avoiding White's continuation mentioned below.}) 14. cxb6 (14. Ra1
$5 Nec6 15. Qe2 a6 16. O-O Nc4 17. Bc3 {offers White good compensation for the
pawn, as the bishop a4 has no obvious way of returning into play - a direct
consequence of ...b7-b5.}) 14... Qxb6 15. O-O (15. Qe2 Rb8 16. Nb1 Bb5 $17 {
Eley,B-Webb,S Eastbourne/ East Sussex 1973 (0-1, 33)}) 15... Nec6 16. Qe2 Rb8
17. Rc3 Be7 18. Rfc1 O-O 19. Bb1 Rfc8 20. Qd3 g6 21. Qe3 Qd8 $17 {Kinlay,
J-Webb,S London 1973 (0-1, 36) In all these games White does not have
compensation for the strong pawn on b3.} *

