1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. a3 c4 7. Nbd2 Na5 8. Be2 {
White's most consistent strategy is to make progress with development and
start a slow positional kingside attack. For immediate purposes the last move
achieves this fastest.} ({But in the long run, the more popular} 8. g3 {
(examined in the next lines) tends to be more useful.}) 8... Bd7 9. O-O (9. Rb1
{avoids the c1-bishop's exchange after ...Nb3, thus preparing the quick knight
manoeuvre before castling. But at the same time it causes some piece jam.} Ne7
10. Nf1 Qb3 11. Bf4 (11. Qd2 Ba4 $11 {more or less forces the favourable
exchanges after 12.Bd1, as after} 12. Ne3 $2 Qa2 $19 {the rook is doomed.})
11... Ba4 12. Qxb3 Bxb3 {After the queen exchange there are less kingside
dangers and Black can become ambitious on this wing.} 13. Ne3 {Preventing ...
Bc2.} Ng6 14. Bg3 h5 15. h4 Be7 16. Ng5 Bd8 17. Nh3 Nc6 18. Nf4 Nxf4 19. Bxf4
Ne7 20. Bg5 Ng6 21. Bxd8 Rxd8 22. g3 Ba4 23. Kd2 Kd7 24. Rbf1 Ne7 25. Ng2 Rh6
26. Nf4 Rdh8 $11 {Sveshnikov,E (2530)-Eingorn,V (2525) Sochi (Russia) 1985 (1/
2-1/2, 51) There is not much any of the players can do to unbalance the
position.}) 9... Ne7 10. Rb1 ({The regrouping} 10. Re1 h6 11. Bf1 {runs into}
g5 $5 $146 {as White lacks breathing space for his minor pieces.}) 10... h6 {
Now and later this modest and mysterious move is useful, even though Black can
choose a slightly later moment to play it. It not only prevents Ng5 and Bg5,
but also creates the possibility for a counterattack with ...g7-g5.} 11. Re1
Qc7 {We will see a lot of this regrouping, which is my favourite plan, even
though not the only one possible. By transferring the knight to b6 and the
bishop to a4, Black completely stabilizes the queenside.} 12. Nf1 Nc8 13. Bf4 {
The most active way to continue development. The bishop makes use of the fact
that the g3-square is available in the absence of g2-g3, to retreat if
attacked by a knight or pawn.} (13. N3d2 {looks more like a counter-developing
move.} Nb6 14. Bh5 g6 15. Bg4 h5 16. Bh3 Ba4 17. Qf3 Bc2 {A rare achievement
in this line, if White displays a minimum of care.} 18. Ra1 Be7 19. Ne3 Bd3 20.
g3 Rh7 21. Ng2 g5 22. g4 hxg4 23. Bxg4 f5 24. Bh5+ Kd7 25. b4 Nc6 $19 {Smerdon,
D (2507)-Zhang,Z (2595) Istanbul 2012 (0-1, 38)}) (13. Ng3 Nb6 (13... g6 $5 {
comes into consideration, preventing Nh5.}) 14. Bf1 O-O-O 15. Nh5 Ba4 16. Qe2
Kb8 17. Bf4 Ka8 18. g4 Rc8 19. Bg3 {Miljanic,B (2435)-Dimitrov,V (2475) Tivat
1997 (1/2-1/2, 25)} Nd7 20. Bg2 g6 21. Nf6 Qd8 22. h4 Nc6 23. g5 Ne7 $11) ({If
} 13. h4 {, Black should simply continue his plan with} Nb6) 13... Nb6 14. Qd2
Be7 $5 ({In principle there is nothing wrong with} 14... g5 15. Bg3 Be7 {
, but it makes sense to make all the preparatory moves before starting to
advance the pawns, as White's h2-h4 has by no means one-sided consequences.})
15. h4 {Preventing Black's gain of space but weakening the king and creating
the risk of an attack along the h-file after a later ....g7-g5.} (15. Ne3 g5
16. Bg3 O-O-O $132) 15... O-O-O 16. Qe3 (16. h5 {by no means blocks the
kingside. In fact, it offers Black ideas for counterplay.} Rdg8 17. N1h2 Ba4 ({
SInce White has strongly committed himself on the kingside, Black could also
do without this programmed move:} 17... g5 18. hxg6 Rxg6 19. Bg3 Qd8 $36) 18.
Bg3 Qd8 19. Rf1 {Kononenko,D (2472)-Ljukin,S (2343) Alushta 2006 (1-0, 34)} g6
$15) (16. Bg3 Rdg8 17. h5 Qd8 18. N3h2 Kb8 19. Bg4 Ka8 20. Ne3 Qf8 21. f4 f5
22. Bf3 (22. exf6 gxf6 $132 {followed by ...f6-f5 offers counterplay along the
g-file and the possibility to transfer one of the knights to e4, as} 23. f5 $2
exf5 $19 {loses a piece.}) 22... g5 23. hxg6 h5 24. Bf2 Nb3 25. Qe2 h4 $17 {
Degraeve,J (2586)-Arencibia Rodriguez,W (2534) Guelph 2002 (0-1, 69)}) (16. Ng3
Rdg8 (16... Ba4 $5 {avoids the tactical possibility mentioned below.}) 17. Nh5
(17. Nf5 $5 exf5 18. e6 Bd6 19. exd7+ Nxd7 20. Bxd6 Qxd6 $13 {does not seem to
offer White more than just some compensation for the pawn.}) 17... Qd8 18. Bg3
Ba4 19. Bf1 Nd7 {After the knight has fulfilled its first job, it returns into
play via a different route.} 20. Qf4 Bc2 ({Black can avoid the exchange
sacrifice with} 20... Qf8 21. Rbc1 g5 $15) 21. Qxf7 Nf8 {Threatening to win a
piece with ...Bg6} 22. Nf4 Bxb1 23. Rxb1 Qd7 $15 {, with insufficient white
compensation for the exchange.}) 16... Rdg8 17. h5 {After the natural ...Qd8
there would be no other way to fight against ...g7-g5 anyway.} Qd8 (17... Ba4
$5 {threatening ...Bc2 is likely to force a draw by repetition already.} 18.
Rbc1 Nb3 $11 19. Rc2 $2 Na1 $17) 18. N3d2 Kb8 19. Bg4 Ka8 20. Qf3 Qf8 (20... g5
$5 21. Bh2 Rf8 22. Ne3 Ba4 23. Qh3 Qd7 $11) 21. Ne3 Ba4 ({Black might have
rejected} 21... f5 $5 {on account of} 22. Bxf5 {, but this is insufficient:}
exf5 23. Nxd5 Nxd5 24. Qxd5 Qd8 25. Nxc4 Nxc4 26. Qxc4 Bc6 $17) 22. Qh3 Bg5 23.
Qf3 g6 24. hxg6 Rxg6 25. Bh5 Rg7 $36 {Black has the initiative already.} 26.
Bxg5 $2 {White should not agree to open the h-file for Black's attack.} hxg5
$17 {Kriebel,T (2320)-Petrik,T (2532) Banska Stiavnica 2010 (0-1, 39)} *

