1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. a3 c4 7. Nbd2 Na5 8. g3 {
This is considered the main line. By developing his bishop to g2 or h3, White
gets some more space for his pieces in the centre.} Bd7 9. Bg2 ({For the more
ambitious} 9. h4 {see the next line.}) 9... Ne7 10. O-O h6 ({This is one of
the cases where Black does better to tread with care. The familiar plan
initiated by} 10... Qc7 {can be met with} 11. Ne1 {followed by f4-f5. The last
move invites White to define his intentions.}) 11. Re1 ({After} 11. Ne1 {
Black can already switch to} O-O-O 12. f4 (12. Qf3 Be8 13. Nc2 Kb8 14. Nb4 Nf5
$5 $11) 12... Nf5 13. Ndf3 Nb3 14. Rb1 {Mendonca,M (2298)-Barata,A (2147)
Vitoria 2013 (1-0, 44)} Kb8 15. g4 Ne7 16. Be3 f5 {Due to his probelms with
regrouping, which is partly a consequence of ...c5-c4, White cannot keep
control on the kingside.}) 11... Qc7 {After the rook has left the f-file,
blocking the knight's retreat at the same time, the main plan is entirely
playable.} 12. Rb1 (12. b4 $2 cxb3 13. Nxb3 Ba4 14. Nfd2 Nxb3 15. Nxb3 Nc6 $17)
(12. a4 $146 {is an interesting attempt to prevent ...Ba4. Its drawback is
that it turns the a-pawn into a permanent target.} Nf5 13. g4 (13. Ra2 Be7 14.
g4 Nh4 $132) (13. b4 $6 cxb3 14. Nxb3 Qxc3) 13... Ne7 14. b4 cxb3 15. Nxb3 Nec6
(15... Qxc3 {allows} 16. Re3 {, which was not available with the knight on f5}
Qc7 17. Nxa5 Qxa5 18. Bd2 {with a certain initiative for the pawn.}) 16. Ba3
Bxa3 17. Rxa3 Nxb3 18. Qxb3 Rc8 $11 {, with excellent play for Black. One of
White's problems is that the bishop on g2 is not doing much while transferring
it to d3 would be time consuming and weaken the king's defence (especially
notable after g3-g4).}) (12. Nf1 {allows Black to occupy the a4-square without
transferring the knight to b6:} Nb3 13. Rb1 Ba4 14. Qe2 O-O-O $11) 12... Nc8
13. Nf1 Nb6 14. h4 (14. Ne3 O-O-O 15. Qe2 {Havranek,M (2280)-Prandstetter,E 
(2370) Decin 1996 (0-1, 53)} Ba4 16. Nd2 Kb8 17. f4 f5 $11) 14... O-O-O 15. h5
{Strategically the most consistent pawn move.} (15. Qe2 Ba4 16. g4 $6 Be7 17.
Ng3 Nd7 18. Bh3 g6 19. Kg2 Rdg8 20. Rg1 {Manea,A (2402)-Marin,M (2543)
Olanesti 2018 (0-1, 57)} g5 $1 $15 {This game has been examined in the latest
strategic article.}) 15... Be7 16. Ne3 (16. N3h2 {Piorun,K (2633)-Socko,M 
(2458) Katowice 2018 (1-0, 53)} Ba4 17. Qe2 Qd7 18. Ne3 Qe8 19. f4 g6 20. Bh3
Qg8 $11) 16... Rdg8 17. Ng4 Ba4 18. Qe2 Nd7 19. Bf4 Kb8 20. Ne3 Nb6 21. Bh3 a6
22. Nd2 {1/2-1/2 Alvarez Pedraza,A (2526)-Rakhmanov,A (2582) San Cristobal 2012
} Rf8 $5 {This removes the rook from the h3-bishop's range, preparing to
harass the other bishop with ...g7-g5.} ({But the immediate} 22... g5 $146 {
is also possible.} 23. hxg6 fxg6 24. Bxe6 g5 25. Bxg8 Rxg8 26. Qg4 Qd8 27. e6+
gxf4 28. Qxf4+ Ka7 {with reasonable, but not threatening white compensation.})
23. Ng2 {opens a retreat square but leaves c2 undefended.} (23. Kh2 g5 24. hxg6
fxg6 $17) (23. g4 {clears the bishop's retreat but almost buries its colleague
alive.} g6 $15) 23... Bc2 24. Nxc4 Bxb1 25. Nxa5 Bh7 $15 *

