1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. a3 c4 7. Nbd2 Na5 8. g3 Bd7
9. h4 {This is intended to be an improved version of the previous line. White
prepares the bishop's development to h3 while also gaining space. The global
regrouping of the other pieces may also vary, as we will see.} Ne7 10. Bh3 h6 {
Abstractly, I still prefer the move order based on advancing the h-pawn at an
early stage, even though the commitment implied by h2-h4 allows Black to
switch to the main plan immediately:} (10... Qc7 11. O-O Nc8 12. Ne1 {A
similar manoeuvre was the reason why spending a waiting tempo on ...h7-h6 was
useful in the previous line. But now, after f2-f4, Black wants to have the
option to freeze the kingside with ...h7-h5.} Nb6 13. f4 g6 14. h5 ({The
critical test, as after} 14. Qe2 O-O-O 15. Ng2 {as in Lyell,M (2219)-Cobb,J 
(2423) Basingstoke 2012 (0-1, 52), Black can consider} h5 {. In the game he
took some positional risk and eventually won.}) 14... O-O-O 15. Kh2 Be7 16. Ng2
Rdg8 {followed by the familiar ...о Bd8 and White will soon have to count
with ...gxh5 or ...g6-g5.}) 11. O-O Qc7 12. h5 ({After} 12. Ne1 {Black can
deviate from the main plan in the usual way:} O-O-O 13. Ng2 (13. f4 h5 {
takes the sting out of any white kingside ideas, as the knight e7 offers
sufficient defence over f5.}) 13... Kb8 14. h5 Nc8 15. Ne3 Be7 16. Rb1 Nb6 17.
Qe2 {Ni,H (2660)-Hossain,E (2496) Kolkata 2012 (1/2-1/2, 42)} Rdg8 18. Kh2 g6
$36) 12... O-O-O $1 {After White's last move, the knight should stay on e7 to
over-defend f5 and sustain ...g7-g6(5).} ({After} 12... Nc8 {White can start
his attack in an active way:} 13. Nh4 Be7 14. Qg4 Rg8 (14... Bxh4 $6 15. Qxg7
Rf8 16. gxh4 $16 {Paehtz,E (2487)-Gomes,M (2387) Bhubaneswar 2013 (1-0, 33)})
15. Ndf3 Bxh4 16. Nxh4 {, with certain kingside pressure.}) 13. Nh4 {As we
know already, this is the typical way to prepare the attack in this concrete
line.} (13. Ne1 {is simplest neutralized by} g5 $11 {For instance, the
over-ambitious} 14. f4 {runs into} Nf5 15. Qf3 gxf4 16. Qxf4 f6 $15 {White
experiences king safety problems.} 17. exf6 $2 Bd6 $19) (13. Re1 Kb8 14. Rb1 g5
15. hxg6 Nxg6 {followed by ...Be7, ...Rdg8 and ...h5-h4, with an obvious
initiative.}) (13. a4 {once again is an untested idea:} Kb8 14. Re1 (14. b4
cxb3 15. Nxb3 Nxb3 16. Qxb3 Nc6 17. Ba3 Na5 18. Qc2 Bxa3 19. Rxa3 f5 $11) 14...
Rc8 15. Nh2 g5 $132) 13... g5 {A well timed move, before White plays f2-f4.}
14. Ng2 (14. hxg6 {clears space for Black's counterplay.} fxg6 15. Ng2 ({After
} 15. f4 {, Black is not forced to immediately block the wing with 15...h5, as
he can also consider to prepare ...g6-g5 with} Rg8 $15) 15... Nf5 16. g4 Ne7
17. f4 h5 {For king's safety reasons White has to play} 18. g5 {when Black's
advantage may be rather symbolic, as staying prepared for a break with f4-f5
and building up a massive pawn queenside attack is not simple.}) 14... Bg7 $11
15. f4 ({It would have been safer to keep manoeuvring with} 15. Ne3 $11) 15...
f5 $15 16. g4 {Strategically ambitious but concretely unsound as the king
