1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bd3 {This is a flexible move, but
it allows Black to transpose to a reasonable isolani position.} c5 {By far not
the most popular move, but my favourite one, as it leads to similar play as in
our main line after 3.Nd2.} ({If Black is happy with an easy draw he can
maintain symmetry for a long time, of course, starting with} 5... Bd6 6. O-O
O-O {But actually even here there are ways of fighting for an advantage as in
the following recent top game, in which play transposed to the Exchange French
after 5.d3 (instead of 5.d4 or 5.Nc3) 5...Nf6 6.d4 d5.} 7. Bg5 h6 8. Bh4 Nc6 $5
({This rare move is the first sign that Black is playing for more than just
equality, by trying to break the symmetry. There is nothing wrong after the
most popular continuation} 8... Bg4 {. Hard to say whether Anand was heading
straight for a draw or had discovered a hidden way to convert his extra tempo
into some microscopic advantage.}) 9. c3 g5 {The merits of the resolute
advance of the g-pawn are less visible than in the game against Kramnik, but
White's last move, wasting a developing tempo to consolidate the centre,
offers some abstract justification.} 10. Bg3 Ne4 ({Strictly speaking a novelty,
but the only other game reaching the position after White's last move was
played 131 years ago! Black's manoeuvring was rather clumsy and he soon found
himself in a passive position:} 10... Bg4 11. Nbd2 Ne7 12. Qc2 Nh5 13. Rae1 Qd7
14. Ne5 {Metger-Blackburne,J Frankfurt 1887.}) 11. Bxd6 ({In view of some
lines given below,} 11. Nbd2 {looks more flexible, with the idea of
transposing to either of them after 13...f5 14.Bxd6. Anand might have feared}
Nxg3 {but then} 12. fxg3 $5 {would have offered White chances to set up
pressure along the weakened f-file.}) 11... cxd6 {The most consistent move,
keeping control over e5 in order to continue the attack with ...f7-f5. The
strategic risk involved by creating himself double pawns is irrelevant at this
stage, as White's minor pieces cannot attack d5 easily.} 12. Nfd2 {After this
counter developing move Black has little to fear. Caruana confessed he
considered Bc2-b3 (now or on the next move) to be critical, but could not
remember what he had analyzed some time ago.} ({The most natural continuation
is} 12. Nbd2 {, of course. SInce 12...f5 13.Qb3 is likely to cause some
problems,} Qe7 {followed by ...f5 soon is better.}) ({The other critical line
is} 12. Qb3 Be6 13. Qxb7 Ne7 $5 14. Qb3 Ng6 15. g3 f5 {Due to his better
development, a direct consequence of the time wasted by the white queen, Black
has excellent attacking chances for the pawn.}) 12... f5 13. Na3 {Anand seems
to have lost his sense of danger in this game, as he develops in a contorted
and slow way, allowing Black to build up his attack.} Be6 14. Nc2 Nxd2 15. Qxd2
f4 {Black has exchanged his active knight to reach a perfect kingside
attacking structure. It is interesting that White did not manage to find a
good way to regroup his minor pieces, as Black's pawns control many important
squares. Anand,V (2760)-Caruana,F (2822) Stavanger 2018 (0-1, 44)}) 6. dxc5 {
This move offers Black a free tempo, as he usually develops the bishop before
White captures on c5. But most of my opponents so far seem to have feared ...
c5-c4 so this is precisely the way they reacted, justifying a separate line
for what is basically an inferior move. If anything, the games are instructive
for the general ideas in this structure.} (6. Qe2+ Be7 7. dxc5 O-O 8. Be3 Re8
9. b4 $2 a5 10. c3 axb4 11. cxb4 Ng4 $19 {White's vulnerability along the
e-file and the long dark diagonal; are decisive, Kastner,O (2072)-Cerveny,P 
(2289) Policka 2015 (1/2-1/2, 40)}) (6. c3 {is rather modest and can be
answered with} Nc6 {, when Black already has the option to create a completely
equal position with ...cxd4.}) 6... Bxc5 7. O-O O-O 8. Nc3 {Trying to give
play independent character with respect to the 3.Nd2 c5 system.} (8. Nbd2 Nc6
9. Nb3 Bb6 10. c3 Bg4 {offered Black active play, eventually resulting in a
beauty prize!} 11. Be2 Re8 $1 12. Nbd4 (12. Nfd4 Rxe2 $1) (12. Bg5 Qd6 13. Bh4
Ne4 $17) 12... Nxd4 13. Nxd4 $2 (13. cxd4 Qd6 $15) 13... Rxe2 $1 14. Nxe2 (14.
f3 Qe7 15. fxg4 Qe4 16. Rf2 Re1+) 14... Qe7 15. Re1 (15. Be3 Bxe3 16. fxe3
Qxe3+ 17. Rf2 Ne4 18. Qd4 Qxf2+ 19. Qxf2 Nxf2 20. Kxf2 Bxe2 21. Kxe2 f6 $17)
15... Re8 $19 {Baches Garcia,G (2389)-Marin,M (2548) Erts 2012 (0-1, 28)}) (8.
Bg5 Nc6 9. Nbd2 h6 10. Bh4 g5 11. Bg3 Nh5 12. Nb3 Nxg3 13. hxg3 Bb6 $11 {
Ameir, M (2290)-Abdel Razik,K (2430) Cairo 2015 (1/2-1/2, 39)}) 8... Nc6 9. Bg5
Be6 ({I did not wish to offer to my young too much activity after} 9... h6 10.
Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Nxd5 Qxb2 12. Rb1 Qxa2 {, even though objectively Black may be
OK.}) 10. Qd2 Re8 ({Once again, I opted for safety at this stage of the game.
I calculated} 10... h6 11. Bxh6 gxh6 12. Qxh6 Re8 13. Ng5 Bf8 14. Bh7+ Kh8 15.
Qh4 Kg7 {, concluding that Black should have no problems, but with the king
exposed, things could turn irrational in the least expected moment.}) 11. a3 {
Probably intended as a measure against ...d5-d4 after the planned Rffe1.} (11.
Rfe1 {was in fact possible as} d4 $2 {leads to trouble after} 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13.
Ne4 $16 {But White may need to play a2-a3 slightly later anyway and, besides,
the last move also avoids ...Nb4.}) 11... h6 12. Bh4 (12. Bxh6 gxh6 13. Qxh6
Bf8 14. Qg5+ Bg7 $17) 12... Be7 13. Rfe1 a6 14. Rad1 Qb6 15. Qc1 Rad8 16. h3
Rd7 17. Rd2 {Both players have regrouped thoroughly, but Black has some more
space due to his well defended and unblocked isolani.} Nh5 18. Rxe6 {To tell
the truth, I have missed this, but I soon understood that with the queen
passive on c1 it should not work too well.} (18. Bxe7 Rdxe7 $11 19. Rde2 $6 Qc7
$15) 18... fxe6 19. Bg6 Rf8 20. Bxh5 (20. Bxe7 Rxf3 21. Bxh5 Rxc3 22. bxc3 Rxe7
$11) 20... Rxf3 21. Na4 Qa5 22. Bxf3 (22. Bxe7 Rf5 23. Bg4 Re5 24. Bh4 Qxa4 25.
Bg3 Re7 26. Bxe5 Nxe5 $11) 22... Bxh4 23. Nc3 Re7 (23... Bg5 24. Qe1 $15) (
23... Ne5 $1 {leaves White helpless against the threat to spoil the kingside
structure with ...Nxf3+, for instance} 24. Qd1 (24. Be2 Bg5 $19) 24... Rf7 25.
Bh5 g6 26. Bg4 Qb6 $17) 24. Qe1 Bf6 25. Rd1 Bxc3 $6 (25... Qb6 26. Rb1 Ne5 $15)
26. bxc3 Qxa3 27. c4 {and White achieved enough counterplay to reach a draw in
Deac,B (2575)-Marin,M (2543) Olanesti 2018 (1/2-1/2, 42)} *

