1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bd3 c5 6. O-O {This is the
critical continuation, aiming to provoke Black into wasting a tempo when
re-capturing on c5.} Nc6 ({I prefer to keep the structure intact even though
this implies wasting a tempo with respect to the previous line. Objectively,
there is nothing wrong with} 6... c4 {though. In a classical game between
legends White eventually won after} 7. Re1+ ({Actually I am a bit reluctant to
play the position arising after} 7. Be2 Bd6 8. b3 cxb3 9. axb3 Nc6 {, as I
prefer having a central pawn mass myself.}) 7... Be7 8. Bf1 {Kasparov,G (2770)
-Kortschnoj,V (2610) Tilburg 1991 (1-0, 45), but objectively there should be
no major problems for Black here, either.}) 7. Re1+ ({The other way to try to
exploit the king's prolonged stay in the centre is} 7. Bg5 cxd4 (7... Be7 8.
dxc5 O-O 9. Nc3 {, planning to meet 9...Bxc5 with 10.Nxd5! Qxd5 11.Bxf6 gxf6?
12.Bxh7+ may cause some problems:} h6 {Mitbreit,D (2320)-Kobalia,M (2430)
Moscow 1995 (1/2-1/2, 20)} 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Nxd5 Bxb2 12. Rb1 Ba3 13. c4 Bxc5
14. Bc2 Ne7 15. Qd3 {, and Black has to weaken his kingside with} f5 $14) 8.
Re1+ Be6 9. Nbd2 (9. Bf5 {is best met with} Bb4 10. c3 dxc3 11. Nxc3 O-O 12.
Bxe6 fxe6 13. Rxe6 Qd7 14. Re2 Rad8 {, for instance} 15. Qd3 h6 16. Bxf6 Rxf6
17. Rd1 Qf7 $11 18. Nxd5 $2 Rfd6 $11) 9... Bc5 10. Nb3 Bb6 11. a4 a6 {Even if
White retrieves the pawn on d4, Black will have a normal isolani position.}) (
7. c3 {is just modest.} Be7 (7... cxd4 $11) 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Re1+ Be6 10. Ng5 $6
O-O 11. Nxe6 fxe6 12. Rxe6 Bxf2+ {Kennemann,R (1820)-De Boer,R (1969) Goch
2014 (1/2-1/2, 27)} 13. Kxf2 Ne4+ 14. Ke2 Qh4 $19) 7... Be7 8. dxc5 (8. Bg5 O-O
9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. c3 h6 11. Be3 (11. Bh4 g5 12. Bg3 Ne4 $15) 11... Bxe3 12. Rxe3
Bg4 13. Nbd2 Qc7 (13... d4 $11) 14. Qa4 {( Larrua Gonzalez,F (2298)-Pozo Vera,
S (2452) Havana 2014 1/2-1/2, 14)} Qb6 15. Rae1 Rad8 $11 {, followed by ..
d5-d4 soon.}) 8... O-O 9. Nbd2 (9. Be3 {fails to keep the extra pawn.} Ng4 10.
Qd2 Nxe3 11. Qxe3 {Angyan,G (1993)-Kuenitz,K (1820) Benidorm 2006 (1/2-1/2, 34)
} Qa5 12. Nc3 Bxc5 13. Qf4 {White has gained some activity, but Black has more
than one way to maintain equality despite complications:} Be6 (13... Nb4 $11
14. Bxh7+ Kxh7 15. a3 Nxc2 16. Re5 f6 17. Rh5+ Kg8) (13... h6 14. Nxd5 Bxf2+
15. Kxf2 Qxd5 $11) 14. Ng5 h6 15. Nxe6 (15. Nh7 Rfe8 16. Nf6+ gxf6 17. Qxh6 f5)
15... fxe6 16. Qg4 Bxf2+ 17. Kh1 Bxe1 18. Qxe6+ Kh8 {[%cal Gc6b4]} 19. Nxd5 (
19. Qg6 Rf1+ 20. Bxf1 Ne5 21. Qf5 Bxc3 22. bxc3 Qxc3) 19... Nb4 20. Nxb4 Qxb4
21. Qg6 Kg8 $11) (9. h3 Bxc5 10. Nc3 a6 11. Bg5 h6 12. Bh4 (12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13.
Nxd5 Qxb2 14. Qd2 Nd4 $11) 12... Be6 13. a3 Re8 14. Qd2 {Thesing,M (2437)
-Poldauf,D (2404) Germany 2003 (1/2-1/2, 68)} Be7 $11) 9... Bxc5 10. Nb3 Bb6 $5
({During the game I found this more active than} 10... Bd6 {, when after} 11.
h3 {Black does not have any active plan and needs to start simplifications with
} h6 12. Nbd4 Bd7 13. c3 Re8 14. Rxe8+ Qxe8 15. Be3 Qe7 16. Qc2 Re8 $11) 11. h3
(11. Be3 Bg4 12. h3 (12. Bxb6 Qxb6 13. c3 a5) 12... Bh5 13. c3 Re8 14. Bxb6
Qxb6 15. g4 Bg6 16. Rxe8+ Rxe8 17. Bxg6 hxg6 18. Kg2 Ne4 $11) 11... Ne4 12. Be3
(12. Bxe4 dxe4 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 14. Rxe4 Bf5 15. Re2 Nb4 16. Ne1 Re8 {retrieves
