1. e4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e5 $5 {An original system with neo-romantic tendencies,
as it usually involves a pawn sacrifice.} c5 4. b4 $5 (4. c4 $6 Nc6 5. Nc3 Nge7
6. Bd3 d4 7. Nb5 (7. Ne2 g5 $5) (7. Ne4 Ng6 $19) 7... Ng6 8. Bxg6 hxg6 9. d3 a6
10. Na3 Be7 11. Bf4 g5 $17 {James,D (2239)-Baker,C (2357) Birmingham 2000 (0-1,
27)}) (4. d3 Nc6 5. g3 (5. c3 Nge7 {is likely to force White to enter the
Advance system a tempo down, as the e5-pawn will soon need defence.}) 5... Qc7
6. Qe2 Nge7 7. Bg2 h6 8. h4 Ng6 9. O-O Ngxe5 10. Nxe5 Qxe5 11. Qxe5 Nxe5 12.
Re1 Bd6 13. f4 Nc6 14. Bxd5 Nb4 15. Bb3 g5 $15) ({But of course} 4. d4 Nc6 {
transposes to the Advance Variation.}) 4... cxb4 5. d4 {After having avoided
the d-pawn's contact with Black's c-pawn, White finally occupies the centre.
After a2-a3 he will soon consolidate the central pawn with c2-c3.
Theoretically, this will offer him some kingside attacking chances, but Black
can also make use of White's queenside weaknesses.} ({Another possible move
order is} 5. a3 bxa3 6. d4 Nc6 7. c3 Bd7 8. Bd3 b5 9. O-O (9. Nxa3 b4 10. cxb4
Nxb4 $5 $146) (9. Bxb5 Nxe5 {Consuegra,O-Rosado,E Barranquilla 1999 (0-1, 51)})
9... b4 10. cxb4 Nxb4 11. Bxa3 (11. Be2 Ne7 12. Nxa3 Rb8 13. Nc2 a5 14. Nd2
Nec6 15. Nb3 Nxc2 16. Qxc2 Qb6 $17 {Olsarova,T (2251)-Hoang,T (2490) Plovdiv
2014 (1/2-1/2, 52)}) 11... Be7 12. Be2 Nh6 13. Qd2 a5 14. Nc3 O-O 15. h3 Qb6
16. g4 Rfc8 $15 {Hansen,M (2356)-Svane,R (2543) Denmark 2016 (0-1, 30)}) 5...
Bd7 6. Bd3 ({Another possible scenario is} 6. Be2 Qa5 $5 7. O-O Bb5 8. Bxb5+
Qxb5 9. a3 Nd7 10. axb4 Bxb4 11. c3 Be7 12. Ng5 Nh6 13. f4 O-O 14. g4 Qb6 15.
h3 f6 16. Nf3 fxe5 17. fxe5 Nf7 $17 {Bolding,K (2335)-Kogan,A (2505) France
1998 (0-1, 32)}) 6... Ne7 ({The plan based on} 6... Qa5 {is possible here, too:
} 7. O-O (7. Qe2 a6) 7... Bb5) 7. a3 Nbc6 8. axb4 Nxb4 9. Be2 a6 $5 $146 ({
Imitating Bronstein's queenside plan from the following game, where he
unnecessarily wasted two tempi with his king's knight.} 9... Nf5 10. c3 Nc6 11.
h4 a6 12. g4 Nfe7 13. h5 h6 14. Nh4 Na7 15. f4 Nec8 {Barendregt,J-Bronstein,D
Hamburg 1965 (0-1, 38)} 16. Ng2 Nb6 17. Bd3 Bb5 18. f5 {, with a dangerous
initiative.}) 10. c3 (10. Ba3 Ng6 11. c3 Nc6 12. Bxf8 Nxf8 13. h4 h6 14. h5 Nh7
15. Bd3 O-O 16. Nh4 Na5 17. f4 Bb5 18. Bc2 Nc4 19. Qd3 f5 20. Qf3 Rf7 {Despite
his space advantage, White has no obvious adequate way to carry out g2-g4.} 21.
Rh3 (21. Ng6 Nf8 22. Rg1 Rc7 23. g4 Nxg6 24. hxg6 Qh4+) 21... Rc8 22. g4 Ng5
23. fxg5 fxg4 24. Qxg4 Rf1+ $1) 10... Nbc6 11. Bd3 Nc8 12. O-O h6 13. Ne1 Nb6
14. f4 g6 15. Rf3 h5 16. Ra2 Ne7 17. Raf2 (17. Ba3 Nc4 {leaves the bishop
short of stable squares along the active diagonal.}) 17... Rc8 18. Nc2 Nf5 19.
Bxf5 gxf5 20. Ba3 Ba4 21. Bxf8 Rxf8 22. Nba3 Kd7 $5 $15 *

