1. e4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 {Another interesting move order, delaying d2-d4 and
thus aiming to take us away from the intended repertoire.} Nf6 {The simplest.}
({For once, switching to the isolani is not a good idea:} 3... c5 $6 4. exd5
exd5 5. d4 {, reaching an unfavourable Sicilian.}) (3... d4 4. Ne2 c5 5. c3 {
is playable for Black, but does not suit the French spirit too much.}) 4. e5
Ne4 $5 {This gives the game a completely independent character.} (4... Nfd7 5.
d4 c5 {would transpose to a modest white setup from the 3.Nc3 Nf6 main system,
but Black can avoid that.}) 5. Ne2 {The most consistent move.} (5. d3 Nxc3 6.
bxc3 c5 $11) (5. h4 h6 6. h5 c5 $11) (5. Nb1 Bc5 6. d4 Bb6 7. Bd3 c5 8. Nbd2
Nxd2 9. Bxd2 cxd4 {without obvious white compensation for the pawn.}) 5... Ng5
$5 (5... Bc5 6. d4 Bb6 7. Ng3 c5 8. Bd3 Ba5+ 9. Kf1 Nxg3+ 10. hxg3 cxd4 11. Ng5
h6 12. Qh5 $16 {Jurkovic,H (2386)-Rogulj,B (2452) Kastav 2002 (1-0, 45)}) 6.
Nxg5 ({The second knight retreat offers Black too much freedom:} 6. Nfg1 f6 7.
f4 Nf7 8. d4 c5 9. c3 Nc6 10. Nf3 fxe5 11. fxe5 Be7 $11) 6... Qxg5 7. d4 Qd8 {
We have reached a normal French structure, where the absence of one pair of
knights nullifies Black's space problems.} 8. Be3 ({A typical situation arises
after} 8. c3 c5 9. a3 {, when Black can ignore White's positional threat, as
his possibilities to comfortably regroup have increased after the knight
exchange.} Nc6 10. b4 cxd4 11. cxd4 {Coleto Calderon,J (2114)-Alvarez Abejon,A
(2084) Madrid 2010 (1/2-1/2, 26)} f6 12. Nf4 g6 13. Bb2 Bg7 $11) (8. Nf4 c5 9.
dxc5 Qc7 10. Nd3 Nd7 11. Bf4 Nxc5 12. Nxc5 Bxc5 13. Bd3 {Vega Gutierrez,S 
(2299)-Garcia Carbo,M (2384) Padron 2006 (0-1, 38)} Bd7 14. O-O (14. Qg4 O-O-O
15. O-O f5 $132 16. exf6 $2 e5 $19) 14... Bd4 15. Qg4 Bxe5 16. Qxg7 Bxg7 17.
Bxc7 Ke7 $11) (8. g3 c5 9. c3 Nc6 10. Bh3 cxd4 11. cxd4 Qa5+ 12. Bd2 Bb4 13.
Bc3 Bd7 14. O-O Rc8 15. f4 Bxc3 16. bxc3 {Stankovic,M (2120)-Milicic,T (2025)
Belgrade 1993 (1-0, 43)} Ne7 17. a4 O-O 18. g4 f6 $15) (8. f4 c5 9. c3 (9. Be3
Qb6 10. dxc5 Qxb2 {White is best adviced to force a draw by continuingly
attacking the queen with his rook, as the attempt to trap her fails:} 11. a3
Nd7 12. Bd4 Qb5 13. Nc3 Qa5 14. Bb5 Bxc5 $1 $17 {Kwiatkowski,W (1941)
-Kokoszczynski,J (1873) Jastrzebia Gora 2015 (0-1, 40)}) 9... Bd7 10. Be3 {
1/2-1/2 (51) Fatkhutdinov,G (2174)-Schupaleev,A (2299) Russia 2000} Qb6 11. Qd2
Nc6 12. h4 O-O-O 13. h5 f6 $11) 8... c5 9. Qd2 Nc6 10. f4 Qb6 11. O-O-O Bd7 12.
dxc5 Bxc5 13. Bxc5 Qxc5 14. Nd4 Nxd4 15. Qxd4 Rc8 16. Qxc5 Rxc5 {Optically the
ending looks better for White due to his "good" bishop, but Black has just
enough room for his pieces and little trouble maintaining equality.} 17. Bd3
Ke7 18. Kd2 a6 19. c3 Bb5 20. Bb1 g6 21. Ke3 h5 {In order to start his pawn
attack, White will have to expose himself along the h-file and fourth rank, as
it will be illustrated below.} 22. g3 Bc6 ({I would find a move such as} 22...
a5 {more natural, keeping the rook's mobility along the c-file. White cannot
launch his pawn attack under favourable circumstances:} 23. h3 Rcc8 24. g4 Bc6
25. Kd4 Bb5 26. f5 Be2 27. Rde1 Bf3 $17) 23. Rd4 (23. h3 Bb5 24. g4 Rc4 {
already threatens to exchange on g4 and h1, followed by ...g6-g5 with
counterplay.}) 23... Rb5 24. b3 Rc5 25. Rc1 Bd7 26. Bd3 Rhc8 27. Kd2 Bb5 28.
Bxb5 Rxb5 $11 {Roy Chowdhury,S (2425)-Drozdovskij,Y (2562) New Delhi 2007 (1/
2-1/2, 34)} *

