1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 {An interesting line, aiming to obtain chances for a
piece attack against Black's kingside.} c5 {Previously I thought that theory
held this as insufficient, but now I see no reason to refrain from adopting
this thematic central structures.} (3... Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 {and}) (3... dxe4
4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2 {are the main lines.}) 4. exd5 ({It does not look right with
this queenside structure to block the centre:} 4. e5 Nc6 5. f4 Nh6 6. Nf3 Be7
7. g3 O-O 8. Bg2 {1/2-1/2 (13) Sax,G (2590)-Farago,I (2510) Amsterdam 1979} b5
9. O-O Bb7 $11 {, without the slightest problems for Black.}) (4. Qe2 d4 $5 {
is likely to leave the bishop passive for a long time.} 5. f4 (5. Nf3 Nc6 6. c3
e5 $15 {consolidates Black's centre.}) 5... Nc6 6. Nf3 (6. g3 e5 {allows Black
to strengthen his centre.}) 6... Qf6 $15 7. g3 $2 d3 $1 $19) (4. Bb5+ Bd7 5.
Bxd7+ Qxd7 {rather plays in Black's hands, as it exchanges his passive bishop
and speeds up his development.} 6. exd5 exd5 7. Qe2+ Ne7 8. Nf3 Nbc6 9. O-O
O-O-O 10. d4 Ng6 11. Qd2 Qg4 12. h3 Qf5 {and White needs to worry about ...Nf4
already.}) (4. Nc3 d4 5. Nce2 Nc6 {once again leaves White wonder why he
