1. e4 e6 ({Some lines examined in this section can arise via the Zvjagintsev
Sicilian after} 1... c5 2. Na3 e6 3. c3 d5 4. e5 Nc6 5. f4) 2. f4 d5 3. e5 {
This simplistic line has a long history, for instance being frequently seen in
the matches McDonnell-De Labourdonnais. I have quoted some fragments from
these games which are still valid to this day.} (3. d3 {is simplest met by}
dxe4 (3... c5 {leads to more complex play after} 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Be2 Nf6 6. e5
Nd7) 4. dxe4 Qxd1+ 5. Kxd1 Nf6 6. Bd3 b6 7. Nf3 Bb7 8. Nc3 a6 9. Ke2 Nbd7 10.
e5 Nd5 11. Nxd5 Bxd5 12. c3 Nc5 13. Bc2 Be7 $11 {Srebrnic,V (2218)-Kovacevic,B
(2455) Bosnjaci 2011 (0-1, 33)}) 3... c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 {Since d2-d4 transposes to
a comfortable version of the Advance Variation for Black, White needs to keep
his d-pawn on the third rank. He has several ways to develop, but none of them
is threatening.} 5. c3 {Preparing the knight transfer to c2.} (5. Be2 Nh6 6.
O-O Be7 7. d3 O-O 8. c3 f6 9. exf6 Bxf6 10. Na3 (10. Nbd2 {Lopes,R (1836)
-Rocancourt Moreira,M (2025) Fortaleza 2015 (1/2-1/2, 59)} b6 $15 {leaves the
d2-knight without perspectives.}) 10... b6 11. Nc2 Bb7 12. d4 Nf5 $11) (5. g3
Nh6 6. Bg2 Nf5 7. O-O ({Delaying castling does not prevent the kind of
counterplay that will also be seen in the main line:} 7. d3 h5 8. c3 h4 9. g4
h3 10. Bf1 Nh4 {, with the initiative.}) 7... h5 8. d3 h4 $5 $146 9. g4 (9. Kf2
f6 $17) 9... h3 10. Bh1 Nh6 11. Ng5 (11. Ne1 Qh4 $17) 11... f6 12. exf6 gxf6
13. Nxh3 f5 14. g5 Ng4 {, with overwhelming compensation for the pawn.}) 5...
Nh6 (5... f6 6. Bd3 Nh6 {was the move order used in McDonnell,A-De
Labourdonnais,L London 1834 (0-1, 53)}) 6. Na3 f6 {Not the most popular move,
but quite a good one, as it prevents White from maintaining the uncertain
character of the position. Black puts pressure on the centre while also
clearing the bishop's path to... g6!} 7. exf6 (7. Nc2 fxe5 (7... Be7 8. d4 O-O
9. Bd3 c4 10. Be2 Bd7 11. O-O b5 12. Ne3 a5 13. Kh1 fxe5 14. fxe5 Nf5 15. g4
Nxe3 16. Bxe3 Be8 17. Qd2 Bg6 $11 {McDonnell,A-De Labourdonnais,L London 1834 
(1-0, 45)}) 8. fxe5 Nf5 (8... Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Qh4+ 10. g3 Qe4+ 11. Qe2 Qxh1 12. d3
$16 {Sedina,E (2353)-Kaczmarczyk,D (2237) Switzerland 2012 (0-1, 47)}) 9. d4
Be7 10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O c4 (11... Bd7 12. b3 Rc8) 12. Be2 Bd7 13. g4 Nh4 14.
Ne3 Nxf3+ 15. Rxf3 Rxf3 16. Bxf3 Be8 $11 {Jiang,L (2337)-Sambuev,B (2523)
Montreal 2012 (0-1, 32)}) (7. d4 cxd4 8. cxd4 fxe5 9. fxe5 Bxa3 10. Bxh6 Bb4+ (
10... Bxb2 11. Bxg7 Rg8 12. Bf6 Qa5+ 13. Kf2 Qb6 $36) 11. Bd2 {Cicak,S (2543)
-Kindermann,S (2519) Germany 2001 (1/2-1/2, 16)} Bd7 $11) 7... Qxf6 8. g3 (8.
d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 Bb4+ 10. Kf2 (10. Bd2 Qxf4 $1) 10... O-O 11. Nc2 Bd6 12. g3 {
Drazic,S (2528)-Zucchelli,M (2145) Arco 2008 (1-0, 33)} e5 $5 13. dxe5 Bxe5 14.
fxe5 Nxe5 15. Be2 Bg4 {, with the initiative.}) 8... Be7 9. Nc2 O-O 10. d4 Nf5
11. Bb5 cxd4 12. cxd4 Nb4 13. Nxb4 Bxb4+ 14. Kf2 Ba5 15. Be3 a6 16. Bd3 Bd7 17.
Bxf5 Qxf5 18. Ne5 Be8 $11 {Lavendelis,E (2317)-Socko,M (2440) Warsaw 2013 (0-1,
